<p>Dose Dependency Of Adverse Events </p>

<p>A comparison of adverse event rates in a fixed-dose study comparing
Venlafaxine 75, 225, and 375 mg/day with placebo revealed a dose dependency
for some of the more common adverse events associated with Venlafaxine
use, as shown in the table that follows. The rule for including events
was to enumerate those that occurred at an incidence of 5% or more for
at least one of the venlafaxine groups and for which the incidence was
at least twice the placebo incidence for at least one Venlafaxine group.
Tests for potential dose relationships for these events (Cochran- Armitage
Test, with a criterion of exact 2-sided p-value &lt; or =0.05) suggested
a dose-dependency for several adverse events in this list, including chills,
hypertension, anorexia, nausea, agitation, dizziness, somnolence, tremor,
yawning, sweating, and abnormal ejaculation. </p>

